did.abstract: Black and white photographs in 1 albums, 1909-1923, containing portraits of employees of a Portland streetcar company, probably Portland Rail, Light and Power Co.

scopecontent.p: The following list is from an album containing portraits of employees (and perhaps applicants) to a streetcar company – most likely the Portland Rail, Light and Power Co., from 1909 to about 1923.

arrangement.p: This list contains the names listed in the album in alphabetical order with a notation of what page each name is located.

note.p: Many of the names in this album are followed by a hire date and abbreviations, which are believed to indicate why the individual left the company. These include F (unknown), FR (falsified records), FQ (falsified qualifications), D (dropped), R (retired or resigned), Res. (resigned), DFR (dropped for falsified records) and NG (unknown).

In almost all cases, only the surname is written in full, preceded usually by the first initials or sometimes a shortening of the first name (“Wm.” for William, “Thos.” for Thomas, etc.). For this list, the processers have expanded shortened names; this includes replacing “Jas.” with “James” and “Jos.” with “Joseph.” In a very few instances, there is a portrait without any notation regarding the subject’s name. In addition, the exact spelling of some names is in doubt due to the illegibility of some of the handwriting in this album. Where this occurred, the name is followed by (sp).
